The path to recovery on Maui has been long, difficult, and uneven. Everyone has had to grieve and rebuild in their own way. But what’s been extraordinary about these past two years is the community and camaraderie that have underpinned everything since that terrible day.

Today, we are starting to see glimmers of hope. Hope is not a naive belief that everything is already okay. Hope is a decision. It's something that we have all had to engage with. And that feeling, through all the struggle, has brought us to a real path to recovery.

On August 11, Maui County will begin accepting applications for nearly $400 million in federal funding to help survivors replace housing lost in the Maui fires.
 
Property owners who lost their primary residence may seek up to $400,000 to help rebuild their home or get reimbursed for reconstruction that has already been completed. Renters who were displaced by the fire may seek up to $600,000 to purchase a single family home.

This announcement is yet another example of RFK Jr. dangerously undermining public trust in vaccines and putting more Americans at risk of preventable disease.

This means all new vaccines would undergo a process where some people receive the vaccine and others receive an inert substance, like a saline shot.

For well-researched diseases, like measles and polio, public health experts believe this practice makes little sense. Not only that, it’s unethical. People in the placebo group would be prevented from receiving a known effective intervention.

RFK Jr. has announced plans to radically change the way vaccines are tested. He wants to require placebo testing for all vaccines, even those for well-researched diseases like measles and polio.

This is a dangerous move that will undermine trust in vaccines that we know work and have saved millions of lives. It ignores decades of scientific and ethical standards. Lives will be at risk.

The Census Bureau has relied on advisory committees to help ensure a fair and accurate census. The Bureau's mission to measure our population, communities, and economy must be carried out in an apolitical way for the public good and to maintain public confidence in the objectivity of vital data. Accurate data is essential so that all communities receive their fair share of federal resources.

The Department of Commerce has terminated the 2030 Census Advisory Committee; the Census Scientific Advisory Committee; and the National Advisory Committee on Racial, Ethnic, and Other Populations. These committees are made up of demographers, statisticians, and other experts who work *for free* and can help the Bureau produce more accurate data for all communities and for decision-makers in both government and the private sector.
